elements.2211.03031_b6de1aefc11a64f0ccb4fc7bc7410: The conditional survival function of a time-to-event outcome subject to censoring and truncation is a common target of estimation in survival analysis
elements.2211.03031_d08e0d80e36e34c16212d36ec0c9f: This parameter may be of scientific interest and also often appears as a nuisance in nonparametric and semiparametric problems
elements.2211.03031_fdff4ce7c0d61d26d069f561737c6: In addition to classical parametric and semiparametric methods (e.g., based on the Cox proportional hazards model), flexible machine learning approaches have been developed to estimate the conditional survival function
elements.2211.03031_1c7bfe91c0e2690338c4b93a82a3b: However, many of these methods are either implicitly or explicitly targeted toward risk stratification rather than overall survival function estimation
elements.2211.03031_b9f979c60690912fd212215ee18a2: Others apply only to discrete-time settings or require inverse probability of censoring weights, which can be as difficult to estimate as the outcome survival function itself
elements.2211.03031_dd013b950df54ff6639c5670e27c7: Here, we propose a decomposition of the conditional survival function in terms of observable regression models in which censoring and truncation play no role
elements.2211.03031_d31beb94936e90ba046bbab29fe43: This allows application of an array of flexible regression and classification methods rather than only approaches that explicitly handle the complexities inherent to survival data
elements.2211.03031_6275eb746f0530213cdb384b1df8a: We outline estimation procedures based on this decomposition, assess their performance via numerical simulations, and demonstrate their use on data from an HIV vaccine trial.

elements.2211.03031_680153ce673dcd75ffde9720d382f: In the analysis of time-to-event data, the conditional survival function is a key quantity of interest
elements.2211.03031_aa3a3c6169c192c5ffa75d3b52e5e: Within the biomedical field, the conditional survival function, which describes the distribution of an outcome variable conditional on a set of covariates, is especially relevant for prediction
elements.2211.03031_e828679b4ef170b70cf3766fb467e: For example, the survival function of a clinical outcome, such as death or disease recurrence, conditional on baseline characteristics may allow a clinician to better understand a patient's medical prognosis
elements.2211.03031_4c7f2dbb77dbf6743907e1ab93469: The conditional survival function also appears as a function-valued nuisance parameter in nonparametric and semiparametric survival analysis problems (see, for example,
elements.2211.03031_3ab3be293ccbec8576a650512646d: Typically, the analysis of survival data is complicated by the fact that the data are subject to censoring, truncation, or both, depending on the study design
elements.2211.03031_cfb1208f4586e0028dfb92a020001: In prospective studies, patients are sampled from the population of interest and followed over time, ideally until experiencing the event of interest
elements.2211.03031_9a83cb806a3a36ecc13daf768cb84: However, occurrence of competing events, loss to follow-up, or study termination may preclude observation of the event time
elements.2211.03031_bdc3d792f4a9bb2767c516b1be8e5: Patients who do not experience the event of interest during follow-up are considered right-censored
elements.2211.03031_17e85f3fd262cdaebf9d8f97f9e61: Additionally, patients who have already experienced the event at study initiation are not eligible for recruitment
elements.2211.03031_17abd2d89c479ef326a27ee726b38: This sampling constraint is referred to as left truncation
elements.2211.03031_6ccb9f0b44f976a8a32430efb608b: Conversely, in retrospective studies, a patient must have already experienced the event in order to be recruited into the study, leading to right truncation
elements.2211.03031_cc447ac1df65707684af90d76ed9c: In this design, censoring is generally not a concern
elements.2211.03031_596cdd9fc7eb7b6825b24d3879373: All forms of truncation lead to systematic selection bias.
